    "<a id=\"Sect1\"></a>\n",
    "<h1><span style=\"color: #22689B;\"><strong>1. Introduction</strong></span></h1>\n",
    "<a href=\"#Table_of_Contents\">Go back to the \"Table of Contents\"</a>\n",
    "\n",
    "Wildfires have a long list of socioeconomic impacts, including material and human losses, biodiversity loss, and the advancement of desertification, among others. In addition to these direct impacts, wildfires are also a significant source of pollutant emissions that severely affect air quality and thus public health. Among the main pollutants generated by wildfires are **carbon monoxide (CO)**, a toxic gas released in large quantities due to the incomplete combustion of biomass, and **nitrogen dioxide (NO₂)**, formed in the atmosphere from the reaction of compounds such as **nitric oxide (NO)** and **nitrogen monoxide (NO)**. Additionally, large amounts of **sulfur dioxide (SO₂)**, a gas that contributes to acid rain formation, and **carbon dioxide (CO₂)**, one of the main greenhouse gases, are emitted.\n",
    "\n",
    "Wildfires also generate suspended particles, especially **fine particulate matter (PM2.5)**, which can penetrate deep into the lungs, causing respiratory problems, and reach the bloodstream, leading to various cardiovascular conditions. The combination of these pollutants creates a significant burden on ecosystems, the atmosphere, and exposed populations, especially in areas close to the fires or under the influence of air currents that carry these emissions.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial, we will showcase some Copernicus data sources that allow us to assess pollutant emissions from wildfires and their impact on air quality. To do so, we will focus on three wildfires that occurred on the Iberian Peninsula (Pedrogao in 2017, Losacio in 2022) and in Greece (Alexandroupoli in 2023).\n",
    "\n",
    "<p style=\"text-align: center;\">\n",
    "    <img src=\"img/20230827_Greece.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"vertical-align: middle;\" />\n",
    "    <em><a href=\"https://www.copernicus.eu/sk/node/27660\">Burnt area of the wildfires in in the East Macedonia and Thrace region, Greece 2023. Source: European Union, Copernicus Sentinel-2 imagery.</a></em></p>\n",
    "</p>\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial is designed to be executed using two different datasets. The first is the Copernicus air quality reanalysis product, which will allow us to check the estimated air quality levels for the dates of the study events. The other product contains data on emissions associated with wildfires. Therefore, it is suggested to run this tutorial multiple times using both datasets. It is important to mention that emissions data and air quality data are not the same, so as we will see, the results obtained with one product or the other, while similar, will not be directly comparable.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Used Datasets\n",
    "\n",
    "The Copernicus Service offers a wide variety of environmental data that can be used for multiple purposes. The available products include observational data, remote sensing, modeling, ocean and climate indicators, etc. Each type of data has its own characteristics, such as spatial and temporal resolution, available variables (physical, chemical, biogeochemical), frequency of database updates, and more.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial, we will focus on studying the impact of wildfires on air quality; therefore, we will use data provided by the Copernicus Atmosphere Monitoring Service (CAMS). Among the variety of available CAMS data are reanalysis data and emissions data derived from remote sensing:\n",
    "\n",
    "* **[CAMS Global Reanalysis (EAC4)](https://www.wekeo.eu/data?view=dataset&dataset=EO%3AECMWF%3ADAT%3ACAMS_GLOBAL_REANALYSIS_EAC4)** \n",
    "* **[CAMS Global Biomass Burning Emissions Based on Fire Radiative Power (GFAS)](https://www.wekeo.eu/data?view=dataset&dataset=EO%3AECMWF%3ADAT%3ACAMS_GLOBAL_FIRE_EMISSIONS_GFAS)**\n",
    "\n",
    "These data are obtained through reanalysis and remote sensing. These types of products are characterized by being generated over a spatial grid that provides high spatial and temporal coverage, allowing us to assess information across the entire study area with high resolution and to conduct temporal studies without the need to deal with missing data.\n",
    "\n",
    "The two datasets used in this tutorial will be described in detail in Section [Accessing Data](#Accessing_Data).\n",
    "\n",
    "As can be observed, we will use two different products for our study. First, we will focus our analysis on the air quality levels estimated by reanalysis product, and then we will conduct the same study using emissions data derived from remote sensing. This will allow us to observe the differences between pollutant emissions and the observed air quality.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Set up\n",
    "\n",
    "The first step to working with Python interpreters is usually to import all the necessary tools and libraries from the Jupyter Notebook ecosystem. The following cell compiles all the libraries that will be used during the tutorial:\n",
    "\n",
    "**General Note**: Execute each cell through the <button class=\"btn btn-default btn-xs\"><i class=\"icon-play fa fa-play\"></i></button> button from the top MENU (or keyboard shortcut `Shift` + `Enter`).<br>"
   ]
