    "<a id=\"Sect2\"></a>\n",
    "<h1><span style=\"color: #22689B;\"><strong>2. Accessing Data</strong></span></h1>\n",
    "<a href=\"#Table_of_Contents\">Go back to the \"Table of Contents\"</a>\n",
    "\n",
    "First step to start working with Copernicus data is to download a dataset that contains the data we want to process. To carry out the exercises proposed in this section, the download of data from two different datasets with the following characteristics is required:\n",
    "\n",
    "|  | CAMS Global Reanalysis (EAC4) | CAMS Global Biomass Burning Emissions Based on Fire Radiative Power (GFAS) |\n",
    "| :---: | :---:| :---: |\n",
    "| **Product Identifier** | [EO:ECMWF:DAT:CAMS_GLOBAL_REANALYSIS_EAC4](https://www.wekeo.eu/data?view=dataset&dataset=EO%3AECMWF%3ADAT%3ACAMS_GLOBAL_REANALYSIS_EAC4) | [EO:ECMWF:DAT:CAMS_GLOBAL_FIRE_EMISSIONS_GFAS](https://www.wekeo.eu/data?view=dataset&dataset=EO%3AECMWF%3ADAT%3ACAMS_GLOBAL_FIRE_EMISSIONS_GFAS) |\n",
    "| **Variable names** | Total column Carbon monoxide (tcco)<br>Total column Nitrogen dioxide (tcno2)<br>Total column nitrogen monoxide(tc_no)<br>Total column Sulphur dioxide (tcs02) | Wildfire flux of Carbon Dioxide (co2fire)<br>Wildfire flux of Carbon Monoxide (cofire)<br>Wildfire flux of Nitrous Oxide (n2ofire)<br>Wildfire flux of Particulate Matter PM2.5 (pm2p5fire) |\n",
    "| **Dates** | 11 years of data starting on 01/01/2013 up to 01/01/2024 | 11 years of data starting on 01/01/2013 up to 01/01/2024 \n",
    "| **Frequency** | Daily data at 12H | Daily data at 12H |\n",
    "| **Range of latitudes** | From 34º to 45º | From 34º to 45º |\n",
    "| **Range of longitudes** | From -11º to 5º | From -11º to 5º |\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "\n",
    "There are [two main ways](https://help.wekeo.eu/en/articles/6416936-how-to-download-wekeo-data) to access the different Copernicus products. The most basic method is through the [Data Viewer](https://www.wekeo.eu/data?view=viewer). However, the [HDA API](https://help.wekeo.eu/en/articles/9515753-what-is-the-harmonized-data-access-hda-api) allows for process automation, facilitating the systematic download of datasets. Therefore, this tutorial will focus on how to use this tool to download the datasets we will be working with. However, as the datasets are of considerable size and may take significant time to download, all the necessary data files have already been downloaded and included in the \"data\" directory for this tutorial. Therefore, it is not strictly necessary to run these code cells if you are not interested in this section or if this library is not installed in your working environment.\n",
    "\n",
    "Before focusing on the data download process, we will define a series of constant parameters that will be used for data downloading and in subsequent sections of the tutorial. The following code cell defines a set of variables that will determine the spatial and temporal coverage of the downloaded files, as well as the working dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "Since this tutorial is designed to be run twice, using two different Copernicus data sources. In the cell, among the definition of other parameters, you can see the definition of the parameter `WorkingDataset`. This parameter will define the dataset used in the tutorial. We recommend first running the tutorial using the Air Quality Reanalysis dataset (`CAMS_AQ`), and then modifying the `WorkingDataset` parameter to run the tutorial using the CAMS Emissions dataset (`CAMS_EM`).\n"
   ]
