   "source": [
    "As you can see in the output of the previous cells, NetCDF files contain three different objects:\n",
    "\n",
    "* **Variables**: Multidimensional arrays of data.\n",
    "* **Dimensions & Coordinates**: Special 1D variables used to define the dimensions of each variable.\n",
    "* **Attributes**: Labels that can be attached to any variable or the dataset (global attributes).\n",
    "\n",
    "You can explore these objects by clicking on the icons (paper and hard drive) located to the right of each object.This allows access to the list of particular attributes of each variable and a general visualization of the data. Using these tools, we can learn that in this case we are working with a dataset that includes four variables with a temporal coverage spanning from 2013 to 2023.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, the capabilities to access the data are infinitely greater if we access them using Python commands. Along the next sections of this tutorial, we will show some examples of how data can be accessed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "79caa35e-f27a-46ff-94b2-9a8f097f44b3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id=\"Sect3\"></a>\n",
    "<h1><span style=\"color: #22689B;\"><strong>3. Visualization of Average Climatic Values</strong></span></h1>\n",
    "<a href=\"#Table_of_Contents\">Go back to the \"Table of Contents\"</a>\n",
    "\n",
    "As a first contact with the available data, we will create a map of the four variables included in the dataset. However, since this contains a series of data over 11 years, we will calculate a temporal mean of all the data, which will provide us with an initial approximate idea of the field of the different atmospheric pollutants being studied.\n",
    "\n",
    "The next code cell uses the `.mean()` function, which must be invoked by specifying the dimensions (`dim`) along which the averaging will be performed. The `keep_attrs` parameter allows for the retention of the attributes of the original object (`DS`) in the resulting object (`Mean`).\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4362ffaa-0f6a-4a7e-bf2b-7794a7428418",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Compute Time Average\n",
    "\n",
    "Mean = DS.mean(dim='valid_time',\n",
    "               keep_attrs = True)\n",
    "\n",
    "display(Mean)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31d961ec-248b-45c2-947c-5a0d0cb7447a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The resulting object `Mean` contains the same variables as in the original dataset (`DS`), but with the temporal average; thus, the temporal dimension (`valid_time`) has been removed.\n",
    "\n",
    "The following cell defines a function called `PlotMap`that generates the map of the dataset given as the parameter `Data`. To facilitate understanding, the lines of the function have been divided into three separate groups:\n",
    "1. <u>**Editing basic map features:**</u> This section includes a series of commands to define some aesthetic features of the map, such as the coastline, latitude and longitude gridlines, land mask, country borders, and map lat/lon limits.\n",
    "1. <u>**Command to plot the data:**</u> Since we want to create a color map of ocean variables, we will utilize the [pcolor()](https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.pcolormesh.html) function, which generates a pseudocolor plot of the data. The arguments of this function must be provided in the following order: longitude, latitude, and data values.\n",
    "1. <u>**Final editing commands:**</u> The figure is finalized by including some editing commands, such as the inclusion of a formatted title and the color scale of the plot.\n",
    "\n",
    "Defining a plotting function that allows us to create map charts will be highly useful throughout this tutorial, as from this point onwards, we will be able to generate map charts easily without having to replicate lines of code repeatedly.\n",
    "\n",
    "As can be seen in the following code cell, once the function is defined, it can be used by providing the following input parameters:\n",
    "1. `Ax:` The axis where the map will be placed.\n",
    "1. `DS:` The name of the dataset that contains the data.\n",
    "1. `VarName:` The name of the variable within the dataset that you wish to plot.\n",
    "\n",
    "The function `PlotMap` is designed to include a map on predefined axes `Ax`; thus, before calling the function, it is necessary to create the corresponding objects for the figure (`Fig`) and the axes (`Ax`), which, being the axes of a map, must be defined using some type of cartographic projection. Subsequently, it is possible to call the function to plot one of the variables by its name `VarName`.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "76dd4648-7b9d-4d3a-9fd3-4304f7a61112",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Plot Map of One Variable\n",
    "\n",
    "def PlotMap(Ax, Data, VarName):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    This function compiles the code lines needed to plot a map on a given axis (Ax)\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    #1. Editing basic map features\n",
    "    Ax.coastlines()                                                           # add the coastlines\n",
    "    G = Ax.gridlines(crs=ccrs.PlateCarree(), draw_labels=True, linestyle=':') # add the longitude / latitude lines\n",
    "    G.right_labels = False                                                    # remove latitude labels on the right\n",
    "    G.top_labels = False                                                      # remove longitude labels on the top\n",
    "    G.xlabel_style = {'size': 'small'}                                        # x-axis label properties\n",
    "    G.ylabel_style = {'size': 'small'}                                        # y-axis label properties\n",
    "    Ax.add_feature(cfeature.LAND, zorder=0, edgecolor='k')                    # add land mask\n",
    "    Ax.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, linestyle=':')                           # add country borders\n",
    "    \n",
    "    #2. Command to plot the data\n",
    "    Map = Ax.pcolor(Data['longitude'],          # Longitude data\n",
    "                    Data['latitude'],           # Latitude data\n",
    "                    Data[VarName],              # Values to plot\n",
    "                    cmap='rainbow')             # Colormap set to 'rainbow'\n",
    "\n",
    "    #3. Final editing commands\n",
    "    Ax.set_title(DS[VarName].long_name, fontsize=10, fontweight=\"bold\")     # add a title to the figure\n",
    "    CBar = plt.colorbar(Map, ax=Ax)                         # add the colorbar\n",
    "    CBar.ax.tick_params(labelsize='small')                  # format ticks\n",
    "    CBar.set_label(label=DS[VarName].units, fontsize='small')           # format colorbar\n",
    "    return\n",
    "\n",
    "# Select Default Variable Selecction\n",
    "DefaultVarDict = {'CAMS_AQ' : 'tcno2',\n",
    "                  'CAMS_EM' : 'n2ofire'}\n",
    "\n",
    "VarName = DefaultVarDict[WorkingDataset]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Figure Creation\n",
    "Fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))             # create new figure\n",
    "Ax = plt.axes(projection=ccrs.PlateCarree())  # create axes with the map projection\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot\n",
    "PlotMap(Ax, Mean, VarName)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c5e02295-43c1-4ca2-819d-9bdb0aff5c8a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The default result shows the average spatial distribution of nitrogen dioxide pollution. As can be observed, it is closely associated with traffic emissions and industrial activity occurring in cities.\n",
    "\n",
    "Since the dataset we are working with contains four different variables, we could execute the `PlotMap` function recursively to visualize each of the variables. However, it is more convenient to define a new function (`PlotAQ`) that allows us to visualize the maps of all variables at a glance.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following code cell, we can see that the `PlotAQ` function uses the [subplots](https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.subplots.html) function from [Matplotlib](https://matplotlib.org/) to create a figure with space for four axes arranged in two rows and two columns. Then, the desired plotting function `PlotFunc` is called to include the corresponding map in each of the axes.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "098379e0-5085-4516-beba-aab8900c7bea",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Function to Plot Atmospheric Variables on Subplots with Geographic Projection\n",
    "\n",
    "def PlotAQ(Data, PlotFunc):\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Create a figure with 2 rows & 2 columns\n",
    "    Fig, Axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize=(15, 10), subplot_kw={'projection': ccrs.PlateCarree()})\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Flatten the axes array to make it easier to iterate over\n",
    "    Axes = Axes.flatten()\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Iterate over all variables\n",
    "    for AxI, VName in enumerate(Data.data_vars):\n",
    "        print(AxI, VName)\n",
    "        PlotFunc(Axes[AxI], Data, VName) #, Title, 'Unidades')\n",
    "\n",
    "    return Fig, Axes\n",
    "\n",
    "PlotAQ(Mean, PlotMap)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8c6b5219-dfc9-4ac8-a1ac-954b316a8da2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The resulting figure shows the atmospheric distribution of the pollutants analyzed in the study area. It should be noted that depending on whether the data from the air quality reanalysis `CAMS_AQ` or the emissions associated with wildfires `CAMS_EM` are being used, the interpretation of the results will differ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a90cee25-3afb-4c95-82bc-06b70baaabd8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id=\"Sect4\"></a>\n",
    "<h1><span style=\"color: #22689B;\"><strong>4. Visualization of Average Values During a Forest Fire</strong></span></h1>\n",
    "<a href=\"#Table_of_Contents\">Go back to the \"Table of Contents\"</a>\n",
    "\n",
    "Since the purpose of this tutorial is to evaluate the impact on air quality and emissions from wildfires, the study of two distinct events is proposed. The fire that took place in the Portuguese town of Pedrógão in June 2017, and the fire that occurred in the Spanish town of Losacio in August 2022.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following code cell, a dictionary is included with the date range during which these unfortunate events occurred. Thus, by configuring the `StudyWildfire` variable, it is possible to select which event to study.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7e916d5a-428d-4329-9e21-e0fd48101aa4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "WildfireDatesDict = {'Pedrogao' : ['2017-06-17', '2017-06-24'],\n",
    "                     'Losacio' : ['2022-07-20', '2022-08-30']}\n",
    "\n",
    "StudyWildfire = 'Pedrogao'\n",
    "#StudyWildfire = 'Losacio'\n",
    "\n",
    "DateIni = WildfireDatesDict[StudyWildfire][0]\n",
    "DateEnd = WildfireDatesDict[StudyWildfire][1]\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ae021e84-4460-4cdd-abfb-ddccd619407c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Once the dates of the event to be studied are defined, our first objective will be to create a map of the average levels of air quality (dataset `CAMS_AQ`) or emissions (dataset `CAMS_EM`) associated with this period.\n",
    "\n",
    "Our purpose at this stage is to create a graph that allows us to identify which regions were affected by the wildfire. To achieve this, we will use two functions from the [xarray](http://xarray.pydata.org/en/stable/) library: [.sel()](https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.DataArray.sel.html) and [.mean()](https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.DataArray.mean.html).\n",
    "\n",
    "The [.sel()](https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.DataArray.sel.html) function allows us to access the data directly by the name and value of the dimensions we want to select. This enables us to access the data by exclusively selecting the date range (`DateIni` and `DateEnd`) of the wildfire that was previously chosen.\n",
    "On the other hand, the [.mean()](https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.DataArray.mean.html) function allows us to calculate the mean value of a data array by selecting the dimension we want to work with, in this case, `valid_time`.\n",
    "In the following cell, we apply the above procedure to all variables in `DS`.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "2e53719a-3827-47fd-bce5-e02ffc0e7b06",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Compute Mean During Wildfire Period\n",
    "\n",
    "# Subseting a especific period from the dataset DS\n",
    "WildfireMean = DS.sel(valid_time = slice(DateIni, DateEnd)).mean(dim='valid_time')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print result\n",
    "display(WildfireMean)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "28fe7ce8-c94c-4ef2-9d73-27231999e19f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we have previously defined the plotting functions `PlotMap` and `PlotAQ`, we do not need to reproduce the code to generate the plot. The results can be displayed directly by calling the `PlotAQ` function including now the data averaged in the selected period `WildfireMean`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "65409a4d-1f40-4dc7-a540-d2beece02cb0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Plotting Air Quality During Wildfire Period\n",
    "PlotAQ(WildfireMean, PlotMap)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e4237edc-6c9c-4337-a3db-e319173fcc88",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the case of the Pedrogao fire, by analyzing the air quality values (dataset `CAMS_AQ`), we can observe how the values of Carbon Monoxide, Nitrogen Dioxide, and Nitrogen Monoxide show pronounced peaks that affect a wide region to the west of the Iberian Peninsula at approximately 40.5 degrees North and 8 degrees West."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "efe7a065-8dd5-46c9-8b09-0b29f1e24b06",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "<a id=\"Sect5\"></a>\n",
    "<h1><span style=\"color: #22689B;\"><strong>5. Visualization of Anomaly Values During a Forest Fire</strong></span></h1>\n",
    "<a href=\"#Table_of_Contents\">Go back to the \"Table of Contents\"</a>\n",
    "\n",
    "The absolute value plotting may not show very conclusive results since, in some cases, no matter how high the emissions associated with certain pollutants are, their signal may be masked by the air quality levels in the surrounding areas. To address this, we can calculate the anomalies in the file to highlight regions with infrequent values.\n",
    "\n",
    "Statistically, anomalies of a variable are defined as the difference between the variable and its mean. This way, we obtain a result referenced to the average value, yielding positive values when the variable is above the mean and negative values in the opposite case.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following code cell, the corresponding anomaly calculations are performed for all the variables stored within the working dataset. Thus, we are calculating which grid points showed values above or below the mean during the study period."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c704b9d4-9a03-4e26-86c4-adbb849d1462",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Compute AQ anomalies\n",
    "\n",
    "WildfireAnom = WildfireMean - Mean\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "61eb593a-007d-4b13-8d50-dbbf3754f25e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "While the anomaly data could be plotted using the `PlotMap` function, it is preferable to do so using a R-W-B (Red-White-Blue) color scale centered so that values close to zero correspond to the white color. This way, the generated map will make it easier to distinguish between areas with values below and above the climatic mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following code cell, a new plotting function, `PlotAnomMap`, is defined. This function is very similar to the previously defined `PlotMap` in section [3. Visualization of Average Climatic Values](#Sect3), with the exception that this time a color scale defined as `RdBu_r` is used, and the limits of this color scale are set by calculating the maximum absolute value of the data. To achieve this, a combination of the functions [abs()](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#abs) and [.max()](https://docs.xarray.dev/en/stable/generated/xarray.DataArray.max.html) is used.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7c00fae4-064e-4c23-9d50-4c024b5c8caf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Function to Plot Anomalies\n",
    "\n",
    "def PlotAnomMap(Ax, Data, VName): #, Title, Units):\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    This function compiles the code lines needed to......\n",
    "    '''\n",
    "    # Editing basic map features\n",
    "    Ax.coastlines()                                                           # add the coastlines\n",
    "    G = Ax.gridlines(crs=ccrs.PlateCarree(), draw_labels=True, linestyle=':') # add the longitude / latitude lines\n",
    "    G.right_labels = False                                                    # remove latitude labels on the right\n",
    "    G.top_labels = False                                                      # remove longitude labels on the top\n",
    "    G.xlabel_style = {'size': 'small'}                                        # x-axis label properties\n",
    "    G.ylabel_style = {'size': 'small'}                                        # y-axis label properties\n",
    "    Ax.add_feature(cfeature.LAND, zorder=0, edgecolor='k')                    # add land mask\n",
    "    Ax.add_feature(cfeature.BORDERS, linestyle=':')                           # add country borders\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Command to plot the data\n",
    "    CMapLim = abs(Data[VName]).max(dim=None)                                  # define limits of color scale\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Map = Ax.pcolor(Data['longitude'],          # Longitude data\n",
    "                    Data['latitude'],           # Latitude data\n",
    "                    Data[VName],                # Values to plot\n",
    "                    vmin= -CMapLim, vmax=CMapLim,                              # define limits of color scale\n",
    "                    cmap='RdBu_r')                                             # Define colormap\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Final editing commands\n",
    "    Ax.set_title(DS[VName].long_name, fontsize=10, fontweight=\"bold\")   # add a title to the figure\n",
    "    CBar = plt.colorbar(Map, ax=Ax)                                     # add the colorbar\n",
    "    CBar.ax.tick_params(labelsize='small')                              # format ticks\n",
    "    CBar.set_label(label=DS[VName].units, fontsize='small')             # format colorbar\n",
    "    return\n",
    "\n",
    "# Figure Creation\n",
    "Fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))             # create new figure\n",
    "Ax = plt.axes(projection=ccrs.PlateCarree())  # create axes with the map projection\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot\n",
    "PlotAnomMap(Ax, WildfireAnom, VarName)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b21addf2-6df0-4e75-b867-58437ba5897e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The result shows in red/blue which regions of the Iberian Peninsula are subjected to abnormally high/low values of the variable during the study period.\n",
    "\n",
    "Once we have an adapted function to create anomaly maps, we can use it to generate the combined graph of all the variables under study."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "020bb962-a21c-46a2-9257-46ed5d76bf0a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## Plotting Air Quality During Wildfire Period\n",
    "PlotAQ(WildfireAnom, PlotAnomMap)"
   ]
